hands_on_practices.solution:
We have 
$$\Phi(R,z)=-\frac{GM}{\sqrt{D(R,z)}},\quad D(R,z)=R^2+\left(a+\sqrt{z^2+b^2}\right)^2.$$
At $z=0$ let $D_0=R^2+(a+b)^2$.  Then
1. Radial derivatives:
$$\frac{\partial\Phi}{\partial R}
=GM\,\frac{R}{D_0^{3/2}},\qquad
\frac{\partial^2\Phi}{\partial R^2}
=GM\,\frac{D_0-3R^2}{D_0^{5/2}}.$$
Hence
$$\kappa^2
=\frac{\partial^2\Phi}{\partial R^2}+\frac{3}{R}\frac{\partial\Phi}{\partial R}
=GM\frac{D_0-3R^2}{D_0^{5/2}}+3GM\frac{1}{D_0^{3/2}}
=GM\frac{4D_0-3R^2}{D_0^{5/2}}.$$
2. Vertical derivative:
$$\frac{\partial\Phi}{\partial z}
=GM\,\frac{(a+\gamma)\,z}{\gamma\,D^{3/2}},\quad\gamma=\sqrt{z^2+b^2}.$$
At $z=0$ only the leading term contributes:
$$\nu^2
=\left.\frac{\partial^2\Phi}{\partial z^2}\right|_{z=0}
=GM\,\frac{1+\frac{a}{b}}{D_0^{3/2}}
=GM\frac{b+a}{b\,D_0^{3/2}}.$$
3. Period ratio:
$$\frac{T_R}{T_z}=\frac{\nu}{\kappa}
=\sqrt{\frac{\nu^2}{\kappa^2}}
=\sqrt{\frac{GM\,(b+a)/(b\,D_0^{3/2})}{GM\,(4D_0-3R^2)/D_0^{5/2}}}
=\sqrt{\frac{D_0\,(b+a)}{b\,(4D_0-3R^2)}}.$$
Substituting $D_0 = R^2 + (a+b)^2$ into this expression gives the final result.
